00:12:39,734 --> 00:12:42,400
No visible signs
of bruising,

264
00:12:42,467 --> 00:12:45,066
trauma, or stress.

265
00:12:45,133 --> 00:12:50,066
Common denominators:
same age, same sex, same school.

266
00:12:50,133 --> 00:12:52,066
So what am I missing?

267
00:12:52,133 --> 00:12:53,333
We came here

268
00:12:53,400 --> 00:12:54,800
to talk to the parents.

269
00:12:54,866 --> 00:12:57,500
So, don't you think
that we should head on...

270
00:13:04,567 --> 00:13:07,300
Are you okay?

271
00:13:07,367 --> 00:13:09,567
Who... who are you?

272
00:13:09,633 --> 00:13:10,767
We're here to help you.

273
00:13:13,200 --> 00:13:15,166
I'm Dr. Hood, Stephen.

274
00:13:15,233 --> 00:13:16,999
We met at the hospital.

275
00:13:17,066 --> 00:13:20,550
I... I have to find my mom.

276
00:13:22,100 --> 00:13:23,899
Stephen. Come on.

277
00:13:23,966 --> 00:13:25,237
Breathe deeply.

278
00:13:27,333 --> 00:13:28,600
He's hyperventilating.

279
00:13:28,667 --> 00:13:30,367
Chatham County.

280
00:13:30,433 --> 00:13:32,266
McKinley Elementary
School.

281
00:13:32,333 --> 00:13:34,100
We need an ambulance.

282
00:13:34,166 --> 00:13:35,500
It could be
cardiac arrest.

283
00:13:35,567 --> 00:13:36,467
Mom!

284
00:13:41,933 --> 00:13:43,933
Stephen,

285
00:13:43,999 --> 00:13:45,766
you scared me.

286
00:13:45,833 --> 00:13:47,466
I could have lost you.

287
00:13:47,533 --> 00:13:49,500
I'm sorry.

288
00:13:49,566 --> 00:13:51,166
What happened?

289
00:13:51,233 --> 00:13:52,500
You never went home.
Where did you go?

290
00:13:52,566 --> 00:13:54,867
Hello again,

291
00:13:54,933 --> 00:13:56,366
Stephen.

292
00:13:56,433 --> 00:13:58,199
Dr. Hood?

293
00:13:58,266 --> 00:13:59,533
That's right.

294
00:13:59,600 --> 00:14:01,700
How are you feeling?

295
00:14:02,733 --> 00:14:05,032
Stephen,

296
00:14:05,099 --> 00:14:06,999
tell me what happened.

297
00:14:07,066 --> 00:14:08,612
Stephen,

298
00:14:08,612 --> 00:14:10,166
who are you protecting?

299
00:14:13,199 --> 00:14:14,399
Get it off!

300
00:14:14,466 --> 00:14:15,500
No, Stephen, don't!

301
00:14:15,566 --> 00:14:16,700
He's terrified of needles!

302
00:14:16,766 --> 00:14:17,566
Can we get a nurse?

303
00:14:17,633 --> 00:14:19,266
Right here.

304
00:14:21,700 --> 00:14:23,633
Thank you very much.

305
00:14:23,700 --> 00:14:26,566
The tox panel shows traces
of bufotenin.

306
00:14:26,633 --> 00:14:28,500
What the hell
is bufotenin?

307
00:14:28,566 --> 00:14:29,691
It's a hallucinogenic,

308
00:14:29,691 --> 00:14:33,032
and it's more than capable
of causing a heart attack.

309
00:14:35,333 --> 00:14:37,733
He was with a boy
named Jesse Freeman

310
00:14:37,800 --> 00:14:39,166
out by the swamp.

311
00:14:39,233 --> 00:14:41,099
They were getting high.

312
00:14:41,166 --> 00:14:42,833
He wouldn't tell me with what.

313
00:14:42,900 --> 00:14:43,900
Thank you, Mrs. Brown.

314
00:14:43,967 --> 00:14:45,503
That's... that's helpful.

315
00:14:47,999 --> 00:14:49,600
Jesse Freeman.

316
00:14:49,666 --> 00:14:50,833
Mrs. LaTerriere

317
00:14:50,900 --> 00:14:52,333
mentioned him, too.

318
00:14:52,399 --> 00:14:54,199
Where'd they get the bufotenin?

319
00:14:54,266 --> 00:14:55,867
You can find it
in mushrooms,

320
00:14:55,933 --> 00:14:59,600
but more commonly in the skin
of a very special toad.

321
00:15:01,633 --> 00:15:03,700
That's a black
swamp snake, Rachel.

322
00:15:03,766 --> 00:15:05,533
Don't worry.

323
00:15:05,600 --> 00:15:06,867
He's perfectly harmless.

324
00:15:06,933 --> 00:15:08,900
That right there
is just a baby.

325
00:15:08,967 --> 00:15:10,266
Yum, yum.

326
00:15:10,333 --> 00:15:11,800
Pretty damn tasty.

327
00:15:11,867 --> 00:15:13,933
There's one
right there!

328
00:15:15,233 --> 00:15:16,900
Hood, what exactly
are we looking for

329
00:15:16,967 --> 00:15:19,366
<i>here?
Bufo alvarius.</i>

330
00:15:19,433 --> 00:15:22,032
Colorado River toad.

331
00:15:22,099 --> 00:15:23,399
In Georgia?

332
00:15:23,466 --> 00:15:25,967
That's the species
that carries the bufotenin.

333
00:15:26,032 --> 00:15:27,967
These kids must have got it
somewhere.

334
00:15:28,032 --> 00:15:31,132
This swamp is the closest thing
we got

335
00:15:31,199 --> 00:15:34,132
to a toad's natural habitat
in this area.

336
00:15:40,633 --> 00:15:42,700
Hello.

337
00:15:42,766 --> 00:15:45,956
I know
you.

338
00:15:46,967 --> 00:15:50,700
I got him.

339
00:15:53,666 --> 00:15:55,633
Ribbit.

340
00:15:55,700 --> 00:15:57,066
See, this little guy-

341
00:15:57,132 --> 00:15:59,237
say hello.

342
00:15:59,237 --> 00:16:01,566
When he's agitated
like that,

343
00:16:01,633 --> 00:16:04,633
he secretes this poison,
which is a hallucinogen

344
00:16:04,700 --> 00:16:05,967
bufotenin.

345
00:16:06,032 --> 00:16:07,633
What people normally do
is they...

346
00:16:07,700 --> 00:16:09,299
they burn off
the poisonous element,

347
00:16:09,366 --> 00:16:10,933
and render it harmless;
then they smoke it.

348
00:16:10,999 --> 00:16:14,299
But if it's harmless, then
why did Stephen have a seizure?

349
00:16:14,366 --> 00:16:15,466
Well, I think what

350
00:16:15,533 --> 00:16:17,466
our kids have been doing is, uh,

351
00:16:17,533 --> 00:16:19,733
a thing called "toad licking. "

352
00:16:19,800 --> 00:16:22,425
You, uh, get him agitated.

353
00:16:23,500 --> 00:16:25,488
Kind of like
he is now.

354
00:16:25,488 --> 00:16:27,456
Soon as he starts
to secrete the poison,

355
00:16:27,456 --> 00:16:29,706
you lick it, get very high.

356
00:16:30,099 --> 00:16:31,800
That's sick.

357
00:16:31,867 --> 00:16:33,967
But if toad-licking
caused

358
00:16:34,032 --> 00:16:35,399
the cardiac arrests,

359
00:16:35,466 --> 00:16:37,233
then why didn't the other boys
test positive

360
00:16:37,299 --> 00:16:38,500
for the bufotenin?

361
00:16:38,566 --> 00:16:40,500
Rachel, that's a very
good question.

362
00:16:40,566 --> 00:16:42,066
Well, I got
another one for you.

363
00:16:42,132 --> 00:16:46,300
How does a Colorado River toad
end up in a Georgia swamp?

364
00:16:46,300 --> 00:16:46,967
That's simple.

365
00:16:47,066 --> 00:16:48,333
Someone brought him.

366
00:16:48,399 --> 00:16:49,566
But who?

367
00:16:49,633 --> 00:16:51,700
I think we should ask
Jesse Freeman.

368
00:16:51,766 --> 00:16:54,999
He seems to be
our local toad pusher.

369
00:16:55,066 --> 00:16:57,566
I'm gonna ask you
one more time, Jesse.

370
00:16:57,633 --> 00:16:59,867
Where'd you get the toads?

371
00:16:59,933 --> 00:17:02,700
Stephen Brown
almost had a heart attack

372
00:17:02,766 --> 00:17:04,967
because of it.

373
00:17:05,032 --> 00:17:07,700
You give it to any
of the boys that died?

374
00:17:09,099 --> 00:17:10,199
No way.

375
00:17:10,266 --> 00:17:12,833
I never hang
with any of those losers

376
00:17:12,900 --> 00:17:15,366
except for school

377
00:17:15,433 --> 00:17:17,378
when I got no choice.

378
00:17:18,099 --> 00:17:19,366
Jesse,

379
00:17:19,433 --> 00:17:21,366
why don't you do
your mom a favor

380
00:17:21,433 --> 00:17:22,633
and be straight
with us?

381
00:17:22,700 --> 00:17:24,166
If you cooperate,
I'll get the deputy here

382
00:17:24,233 --> 00:17:26,113
to keep you
out of this.

383
00:17:27,166 --> 00:17:29,099
Tell them, Jesse.

384
00:17:34,237 --> 00:17:35,566
All right.

385
00:17:36,032 --> 00:17:38,378
I took them
from Lizzie Summers' place.

386
00:17:39,066 --> 00:17:41,266
I didn't mean
for anyone to get hurt.

387
00:17:41,333 --> 00:17:43,666
Just wanted to have some fun.

388
00:17:43,733 --> 00:17:45,733
Okay.

389
00:17:46,766 --> 00:17:48,766
Thank you.

390
00:17:49,800 --> 00:17:53,233
What's Stephen's mom
doing here?

391
00:18:20,800 --> 00:18:24,733
Lizzie Summers has been in town
for about three years.

392
00:18:24,800 --> 00:18:26,066
She set up shop out here

393
00:18:26,132 --> 00:18:28,166
as a homeopathic
pharmacist.

394
00:18:35,867 --> 00:18:37,867
Miss Summers!

395
00:18:42,533 --> 00:18:45,466
Deputy, how can I help you?

396
00:18:45,533 --> 00:18:47,132
Miss Summers,

397
00:18:47,199 --> 00:18:49,132
these folks are
from Washington, DC.

398
00:18:49,199 --> 00:18:51,166
They're here
to help us find out

399
00:18:51,233 --> 00:18:53,199
how those young
boys died.

400
00:18:53,266 --> 00:18:55,233
Special Agent Rachel Young

401
00:18:55,299 --> 00:18:57,175
from the FBI.
Hi.

402
00:18:57,175 --> 00:18:59,066
Dr. Jacob Hood.

403
00:18:59,132 --> 00:19:01,433
<i>The Jacob Hood?</i>

404
00:19:01,500 --> 00:19:04,199
Um... I suppose.

405
00:19:04,266 --> 00:19:06,366
I read your paper
on dark matter.

406
00:19:06,433 --> 00:19:08,600
"Unknown,

407
00:19:08,666 --> 00:19:10,933
"intangible, immeasurable

408
00:19:10,999 --> 00:19:13,597
and yet without it,
the heavens would fall. "

409
00:19:14,378 --> 00:19:16,433
I was rooting for you to win
the Nobel Prize that year.

410
00:19:16,500 --> 00:19:18,099
Oh, well, if you were,
you're one of only three people

411
00:19:18,166 --> 00:19:20,132
in the western hemisphere,
but thanks nonetheless.

412
00:19:20,199 --> 00:19:20,833
Yeah.

413
00:19:20,900 --> 00:19:22,833
Do you grow, uh,

414
00:19:22,900 --> 00:19:24,500
<i>sceletium tortuosum?</i>

415
00:19:24,566 --> 00:19:25,999
Oh, yeah, and kanna.

416
00:19:26,066 --> 00:19:28,032
I use it as an
anti-anxiety remedy.

417
00:19:28,099 --> 00:19:30,299
Yeah, but it's much more
than that, isn't it?

418
00:19:30,366 --> 00:19:32,299
Kanna goes back
to prehistoric times.

419
00:19:32,366 --> 00:19:34,900
Early hunter-gatherers used it
as an appetite suppressant

420
00:19:34,967 --> 00:19:36,299
so they could hunt

421
00:19:36,366 --> 00:19:38,199
for days
without going hungry.

422
00:19:40,233 --> 00:19:43,112
But show us where you keep
your Colorado River toads.

423
00:19:47,900 --> 00:19:51,233
You have quite a variety
of dangerous animals

424
00:19:51,299 --> 00:19:52,566
and insects here.

425
00:19:52,633 --> 00:19:53,666
Well, sometimes
the most

426
00:19:53,733 --> 00:19:55,199
dangerous venoms and poisons

427
00:19:55,266 --> 00:19:56,900
serve as lifesavers.

428
00:19:58,363 --> 00:20:01,233
What do you do
with the toads?

429
00:20:01,299 --> 00:20:03,666
Oh, homeopathic
erectile dysfunction medication.

430
00:20:03,733 --> 00:20:05,666
I sell it
over the Internet,

431
00:20:05,733 --> 00:20:07,733
along with other remedies.

432
00:20:07,800 --> 00:20:09,766
Miss Summers,

433
00:20:09,833 --> 00:20:11,233
we found bufotenin

434
00:20:11,299 --> 00:20:13,366
in the blood
of an 11-year-old boy

435
00:20:13,433 --> 00:20:15,733
who nearly had
a heart attack.

436
00:20:15,800 --> 00:20:17,666
Jesse Freeman

437
00:20:17,733 --> 00:20:20,466
said he got the toad
that produced it here.

438
00:20:28,500 --> 00:20:31,433
I keep this shed very secure.

439
00:20:31,500 --> 00:20:33,433
Now, these... these toads,
they breed like rabbits,

440
00:20:33,500 --> 00:20:35,266
so it's very hard
to keep a head count.

441
00:20:35,333 --> 00:20:37,766
Now, if someone wants
to take a chance

442
00:20:37,833 --> 00:20:39,099
and come in and steal one,

443
00:20:39,166 --> 00:20:40,800
I don't see what I can do
to stop it.

444
00:20:40,867 --> 00:20:43,299
But if I've got
to string up razor wire,

445
00:20:43,366 --> 00:20:45,433
I might as well move
back to the city.

446
00:20:45,500 --> 00:20:47,466
Yeah, well, maybe
if you'd stayed in the city

447
00:20:47,533 --> 00:20:50,066
all three of these young boys
might still be alive.

448
00:21:03,900 --> 00:21:06,900
Jesse, Jesse, Jesse.

449
00:21:22,867 --> 00:21:25,299
What's up, honey?

450
00:21:25,366 --> 00:21:29,050
Mommy, why is Jesse so cold?

451
00:21:43,566 --> 00:21:46,833
No!

452
00:21:58,972 --> 00:22:00,987
It's rather late.

453
00:22:00,987 --> 00:22:01,987
I'm sorry
about the hour,

454
00:22:01,987 --> 00:22:04,621
Beatrice, but we need
to speak with you.

455
00:22:04,688 --> 00:22:05,920
My son is asleep.

456
00:22:05,987 --> 00:22:07,554
He's been through
a terrible time.

457
00:22:07,621 --> 00:22:10,487
Jesse Freeman is dead.

458
00:22:10,554 --> 00:22:13,020
Another
heart attack.

459
00:22:16,421 --> 00:22:19,175
Well, I feel for his mother.

460
00:22:20,054 --> 00:22:22,787
God knows she's suffered a lot
because of him.

461
00:22:22,853 --> 00:22:24,521
Nothing to what she'll suffer
now that he's dead.

462
00:22:24,588 --> 00:22:26,128
What were
you doing

463
00:22:26,128 --> 00:22:28,534
outside the Freeman house
today, Mrs. Brown?

464
00:22:28,534 --> 00:22:30,378
I went to give that boy
a piece of my mind

465
00:22:30,378 --> 00:22:32,277
and to tell him
to stay away from my son.

466
00:22:33,478 --> 00:22:35,945
Then I saw that
you beat me to it.

467
00:22:36,012 --> 00:22:39,362
Do you mind if I take a look
at your bathroom, your kitchen?

468
00:22:39,362 --> 00:22:40,113
Why?

469
00:22:40,113 --> 00:22:43,237
To satisfy
my... scientific curiosity.

470
00:22:45,144 --> 00:22:46,487
Help yourself.

471
00:22:46,487 --> 00:22:47,787
Thank you. Through here?

472
00:22:47,854 --> 00:22:49,019
Mm-hmm.

473
00:23:10,784 --> 00:23:12,581
No TV?

474
00:23:12,581 --> 00:23:13,320
We don't have a TV.

475
00:23:13,386 --> 00:23:15,720
It's an unnecessary
distraction.

476
00:23:19,520 --> 00:23:21,553
Did you find what
you were looking for,

477
00:23:21,620 --> 00:23:23,220
Dr. Hood?

478
00:23:24,550 --> 00:23:26,487
Not yet, Mrs. Brown.

479
00:23:30,687 --> 00:23:32,253
Thank you. Good night.

480
00:23:33,378 --> 00:23:36,190
Well, that was an interesting
response to Jesse's death.

481
00:23:36,190 --> 00:23:37,425
I'll say.

482
00:23:38,353 --> 00:23:40,687
I didn't find
any environmental toxins

483
00:23:40,753 --> 00:23:43,019
that could cause
heart attacks in children.

484
00:23:43,086 --> 00:23:44,628
WOMAN ... Could you
get there right away?

485
00:23:44,628 --> 00:23:46,894
Word travels fast.

486
00:23:46,894 --> 00:23:49,113
Freddy St. John's dad heard
about the toad venom.

487
00:23:49,113 --> 00:23:51,479
Went out to Lizzie Summers'
place and busted it up.

488
00:23:51,546 --> 00:23:53,988
I'm gonna go pick him up.

489
00:23:56,675 --> 00:23:58,878
Miss Summers.

490
00:23:58,878 --> 00:23:59,988
We heard what happened.

491
00:23:59,988 --> 00:24:01,316
Are you okay?

492
00:24:01,316 --> 00:24:02,800
No. Not really.

493
00:24:05,112 --> 00:24:08,712
I don't get someone taking
their anger out on plants.

494
00:24:16,646 --> 00:24:17,999
Deputy Larsson is arresting

495
00:24:17,999 --> 00:24:19,733
Neal St. John
at his home.

496
00:24:20,925 --> 00:24:22,932
No, no, I'm not
gonna press charges.

497
00:24:22,999 --> 00:24:24,433
I just...

498
00:24:24,499 --> 00:24:26,800
I can't be angry at a man
who just lost his son.

499
00:24:28,533 --> 00:24:30,266
I could use a drink.

500
00:24:31,466 --> 00:24:32,800
Want to join me?

501
00:24:32,865 --> 00:24:34,433
Sure.

502
00:24:37,191 --> 00:24:38,190
Lizzie?

503
00:24:38,190 --> 00:24:38,987
Huh?

504
00:24:38,987 --> 00:24:41,175
Do you always
wear these gloves?

505
00:24:41,175 --> 00:24:43,099
Whenever I'm handling
poisonous plants.

506
00:24:43,166 --> 00:24:46,499
<i>Poison? You mean, like
Digitalis purpurea?</i>

507
00:24:46,566 --> 00:24:49,633
I didn't see it
in your garden.

508
00:24:49,700 --> 00:24:50,425
Well, I don't grow it here.

509
00:24:50,425 --> 00:24:52,399
There's no need.

510
00:24:52,466 --> 00:24:54,166
It grows wild
all over the fields.

511
00:24:54,232 --> 00:24:55,366
How did you know?

512
00:24:55,433 --> 00:24:57,433
Purple petals.

513
00:24:57,499 --> 00:25:00,099
Can you show us where?

514
00:25:03,965 --> 00:25:05,965
There they are.

515
00:25:10,965 --> 00:25:12,899
<i>Digitalis purpurea.</i>

516
00:25:12,965 --> 00:25:14,533
Mm-hmm.

517
00:25:14,599 --> 00:25:16,599
Foxglove.

518
00:25:17,733 --> 00:25:19,299
Incredibly toxic plant.

519
00:25:20,499 --> 00:25:23,633
Several medicinal properties.

520
00:25:23,700 --> 00:25:25,932
Primarily, uh, heart medication.

521
00:25:25,999 --> 00:25:26,999
Mm-hmm.

522
00:25:26,999 --> 00:25:28,862
Why is it called foxglove?

523
00:25:28,862 --> 00:25:31,499
Well, it's an old wife's tale
from medieval days.

524
00:25:31,566 --> 00:25:32,425
They believed that

525
00:25:32,425 --> 00:25:35,366
the foxes would put
their paws in the flowers

526
00:25:35,433 --> 00:25:38,366
to cover the sound of them
creeping up on the chickens.

527
00:25:38,433 --> 00:25:40,599
Quite deadly, though,
you get the dosage wrong.

528
00:25:40,666 --> 00:25:43,433
I know what you're thinking,
but you're wasting your time.

529
00:25:43,499 --> 00:25:45,132
After the first boy died,

530
00:25:45,199 --> 00:25:48,488
<i>I contacted the hospital
and suggested Digitalis.</i>

531
00:25:48,488 --> 00:25:49,599
